01Gn 18:1 The LORD appeared again to Abraham near the oak grove belonging to Mamre. One day Abraham was sitting at the entrance to his tent during the hottest part of the day.
01Gn 18:2 He looked up and noticed three men standing nearby. When he saw them, he ran to meet them and welcomed them, bowing low to the ground.
01Gn 18:3 "My lord," he said, "if it pleases you, stop here for a while.
01Gn 18:4 Rest in the shade of this tree while water is brought to wash your feet.
01Gn 18:5 And since you've honored your servant with this visit, let me prepare some food to refresh you before you continue on your journey." "All right," they said. "Do as you have said."
01Gn 18:6 So Abraham ran back to the tent and said to Sarah, "Hurry! Get three large measures�� of your best flour, knead it into dough, and bake some bread." / ��Hebrew 3 seahs, about 15 quarts or 18 liters
01Gn 18:7 Then Abraham ran out to the herd and chose a tender calf and gave it to his servant, who quickly prepared it.
01Gn 18:8 When the food was ready, Abraham took some yogurt and milk and the roasted meat, and he served it to the men. As they ate, Abraham waited on them in the shade of the trees.
01Gn 18:9 "Where is Sarah, your wife?" the visitors asked. "She's inside the tent," Abraham replied.
01Gn 18:10 Then one of them said, "I will return to you about this time next year, and your wife, Sarah, will have a son!" Sarah was listening to this conversation from the tent.
01Gn 18:11 Abraham and Sarah were both very old by this time, and Sarah was long past the age of having children.
01Gn 18:12 So she laughed silently to herself and said, "How could a worn-out woman like me enjoy such pleasure, especially when my master - my husband - is also so old?"
01Gn 18:13 Then the LORD said to Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh? Why did she say, 'Can an old woman like me have a baby?'
01Gn 18:14 Is anything too hard for the LORD? I will return about this time next year, and Sarah will have a son."
01Gn 18:15 Sarah was afraid, so she denied it, saying, "I didn't laugh." But the LORD said, "No, you did laugh."
01Gn 18:16 Then the men got up from their meal and looked out toward Sodom. As they left, Abraham went with them to send them on their way.
01Gn 18:17 "Should I hide my plan from Abraham?" the LORD asked.
01Gn 18:18 "For Abraham will certainly become a great and mighty nation, and all the nations of the earth will be blessed through him.
01Gn 18:19 I have singled him out so that he will direct his sons and their families to keep the way of the LORD by doing what is right and just. Then I will do for Abraham all that I have promised."
01Gn 18:20 So the LORD told Abraham, "I have heard a great outcry from Sodom and Gomorrah, because their sin is so flagrant.
01Gn 18:21 I am going down to see if their actions are as wicked as I have heard. If not, I want to know."
01Gn 18:22 The other men turned and headed toward Sodom, but the LORD remained with Abraham.
01Gn 18:23 Abraham approached him and said, "Will you sweep away both the righteous and the wicked?
01Gn 18:24 Suppose you find fifty righteous people living there in the city - will you still sweep it away and not spare it for their sakes?
01Gn 18:25 Surely you wouldn't do such a thing, destroying the righteous along with the wicked. Why, you would be treating the righteous and the wicked exactly the same! Surely you wouldn't do that! Should not the Judge of all the earth do what is right?"
01Gn 18:26 And the LORD replied, "If I find fifty righteous people in Sodom, I will spare the entire city for their sake."
01Gn 18:27 Then Abraham spoke again. "Since I have begun, let me speak further to my Lord, even though I am but dust and ashes.
01Gn 18:28 Suppose there are only forty-five righteous people rather than fifty? Will you destroy the whole city for lack of five?" And the LORD said, "I will not destroy it if I find forty-five righteous people there."
01Gn 18:29 Then Abraham pressed his request further. "Suppose there are only forty?"  And the LORD replied, "I will not destroy it for the sake of the forty."
01Gn 18:30 "Please don't be angry, my Lord," Abraham pleaded. "Let me speak - suppose only thirty righteous people are found?"  And the LORD replied, "I will not destroy it if I find thirty."
01Gn 18:31 Then Abraham said, "Since I have dared to speak to the Lord, let me continue - suppose there are only twenty?" And the LORD replied, "Then I will not destroy it for the sake of the twenty."
01Gn 18:32 Finally, Abraham said, "Lord, please don't be angry with me if I speak one more time. Suppose only ten are found there?" And the LORD replied, "Then I will not destroy it for the sake of the ten."
01Gn 18:33 When the LORD had finished his conversation with Abraham, he went on his way, and Abraham returned to his tent.
01Gn 19:1 That evening the two angels came to the entrance of the city of Sodom. Lot was sitting there, and when he saw them, he stood up to meet them. Then he welcomed them and bowed with his face to the ground.
01Gn 19:2 "My lords," he said, "come to my home to wash your feet, and be my guests for the night. You may then get up early in the morning and be on your way again." "Oh no," they replied. "We'll just spend the night out here in the city square."
01Gn 19:3 But Lot insisted, so at last they went home with him. Lot prepared a feast for them, complete with fresh bread made without yeast, and they ate.
01Gn 19:4 But before they retired for the night, all the men of Sodom, young and old, came from all over the city and surrounded the house.
01Gn 19:5 They shouted to Lot, "Where are the men who came to spend the night with you? Bring them out to us so we can have sex with them!"
01Gn 19:6 So Lot stepped outside to talk to them, shutting the door behind him.
01Gn 19:7 "Please, my brothers," he begged, "don't do such a wicked thing.
01Gn 19:8 Look, I have two virgin daughters. Let me bring them out to you, and you can do with them as you wish. But please, leave these men alone, for they are my guests and are under my protection."
01Gn 19:9 "Stand back!" they shouted. "This fellow came to town as an outsider, and now he's acting like our judge! We'll treat you far worse than those other men!" And they lunged toward Lot to break down the door.
01Gn 19:10 But the two angels�� reached out, pulled Lot into the house, and bolted the door. / ��Hebrew men; also in 19.12, 16
01Gn 19:11 Then they blinded all the men, young and old, who were at the door of the house, so they gave up trying to get inside.
01Gn 19:12 Meanwhile, the angels questioned Lot. "Do you have any other relatives here in the city?" they asked. "Get them out of this place - your sons-in-law, sons, daughters, or anyone else.
01Gn 19:13 For we are about to destroy this city completely. The outcry against this place is so great it has reached the LORD, and he has sent us to destroy it."
01Gn 19:14 So Lot rushed out to tell his daughters' fiances, "Quick, get out of the city! The LORD is about to destroy it." But the young men thought he was only joking.
01Gn 19:15 At dawn the next morning the angels became insistent. "Hurry," they said to Lot. "Take your wife and your two daughters who are here. Get out right now, or you will be swept away in the destruction of the city!"
01Gn 19:16 When Lot still hesitated, the angels seized his hand and the hands of his wife and two daughters and rushed them to safety outside the city, for the LORD was merciful.
01Gn 19:17 When they were safely out of the city, one of the angels ordered, "Run for your lives! And don't look back or stop anywhere in the valley! Escape to the mountains, or you will be swept away!"
01Gn 19:18 "Oh no, my lord!" Lot begged.
01Gn 19:19 "You have been so gracious to me and saved my life, and you have shown such great kindness. But I cannot go to the mountains. Disaster would catch up to me there, and I would soon die.
01Gn 19:20 See, there is a small village nearby. Please let me go there instead; don't you see how small it is? Then my life will be saved."
01Gn 19:21 "All right," the angel said, "I will grant your request. I will not destroy the little village.
01Gn 19:22 But hurry! Escape to it, for I can do nothing until you arrive there." (This explains why that village was known as Zoar, which means "little place.")
01Gn 19:23 Lot reached the village just as the sun was rising over the horizon.
01Gn 19:24 Then the LORD rained down fire and burning sulfur from the sky on Sodom and Gomorrah.
01Gn 19:25 He utterly destroyed them, along with the other cities and villages of the plain, wiping out all the people and every bit of vegetation.
01Gn 19:26 But Lot's wife looked back as she was following behind him, and she turned into a pillar of salt.
01Gn 19:27 Abraham got up early that morning and hurried out to the place where he had stood in the LORD's presence.
01Gn 19:28 He looked out across the plain toward Sodom and Gomorrah and watched as columns of smoke rose from the cities like smoke from a furnace.
01Gn 19:29 But God had listened to Abraham's request and kept Lot safe, removing him from the disaster that engulfed the cities on the plain.
01Gn 19:30 Afterward Lot left Zoar because he was afraid of the people there, and he went to live in a cave in the mountains with his two daughters.
01Gn 19:31 One day the older daughter said to her sister, "There are no men left anywhere in this entire area, so we can't get married like everyone else. And our father will soon be too old to have children.
01Gn 19:32 Come, let's get him drunk with wine, and then we will have sex with him. That way we will preserve our family line through our father."
01Gn 19:33 So that night they got him drunk with wine, and the older daughter went in and had intercourse with her father. He was unaware of her lying down or getting up again.
